==English==

===Etymology===
Greek ''μουοφυδίής'': (single-dual)

====Noun====
'''[[monophysite]]''' 
# A member of an early [[Christian]] [[sect]] who held that [[Christ]]'s [[nature]] is both [[human]] nature and [[divine]] nature at the same time, as opposed to the [[orthodox]] view that Christ, both fully man and fully God, is co-eternal and co-substantial with the [[Father]].

====Adjective====
'''monophysite'''
# Describing the [[belief]]s of a monophysite.
#* ''It followed that however orthodox the Emperor might desire to be, he was forced, if he was a wise man, to take account of the strong bodies of '''monophysite''' opinion, which were to be found in Constantinopal, in Mesopotamia, in Syria and in Egypt.'' - '''1957''' H. A. L. Fisher ''A history of Europe'' Edward Arnold publishers p135.